## OpenClaw Channel Plugin Structure Analysis

Based on my thorough exploration of the IRC, Nostr, and Telegram channel plugins in the OpenClaw repo, here is the complete structure and patterns for designing a new "PulseBoard" channel plugin.

### 1. DIRECTORY STRUCTURE & KEY FILES

All channel plugins follow this consistent layout:

```
extensions/[channel-id]/
├── package.json                      # NPM package metadata with openclaw config
├── openclaw.plugin.json              # Plugin manifest (id, channels, configSchema)
├── index.ts                          # Main plugin entry point (defineChannelPluginEntry)
├── setup-entry.ts                    # Setup wizard entry point (defineSetupPluginEntry)
├── api.ts                            # Public exports barrel (api, runtime-api, helpers)
├── channel-config-api.ts             # Channel-specific config API (often minimal)
├── [runtime-api.ts]                  # Runtime-specific helpers (optional, per-plugin)
├── src/
│   ├── channel.ts                    # Main channel plugin definition (createChatChannelPlugin)
│   ├── channel.setup.ts              # Setup-only plugin (Telegram only, separate setup)
│   ├── accounts.ts                   # Account resolution & listing helpers
│   ├── types.ts                      # TypeScript type definitions
│   ├── config-schema.ts              # Zod schema for channel configuration
│   ├── config-ui-hints.ts            # UI hints for config rendering
│   ├── runtime.ts                    # Plugin runtime store (getRuntime, setRuntime)
│   ├── send.ts                       # Message sending implementation
│   ├── inbound.ts                    # Inbound message handling
│   ├── monitor.ts                    # Provider monitoring/connection management
│   ├── probe.ts                      # Health check/status probe
│   ├── normalize.ts                  # Normalize targets, usernames, IDs
│   ├── policy.ts                     # Security policy resolution
│   ├── setup-surface.ts              # Setup wizard UI/flow
│   ├── setup-core.ts                 # Setup logic/adapter
│   ├── [protocol.ts]                 # Protocol-specific utilities (IRC)
│   ├── [client.ts]                   # Client wrapper (IRC)
│   ├── [nostr-bus.ts]                # Relay bus implementation (Nostr)
│   ├── [nostr-profile.ts]            # Profile management (Nostr)
│   ├── [*.test.ts]                   # Comprehensive test files
│   └── bot/                          # Bot-specific code (Telegram only, 13 files)
└── test/                             # Test fixtures (Nostr)
```

**Key observations:**
- All plugins use TypeScript (.ts) exclusively
- Each has 15-35+ source files depending on complexity
- Telegram is most complex (192 src files) due to bot API intricacies
- Nostr is moderate (29 src files)
- IRC is simpler (36 src files)

